":"1285–1313","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1325":"1325","1225":"1225","1313":"1313","       1255":"1255","1255":"1255","1320":"1320","13 Jul 1291":"13 July 1291","BEF 1291":"before 1291","England":"England","Devonshire,, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crispyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."],"variants":[{"name":"Crisp","meanings":["English: nickname for a man with curly hair, from Middle English <i>crisp</i>, <i>crips</i>, <i>scrip</i>, Old English <i>crisp</i>, <i>cryps</i> (from Latin <i>crispus</i>), reinforced in Middle English by an Old French word also from Latin <i>crispus</i>. In some cases this is possibly a nickname from the personal name   Crispin  .","Americanized form of German <b>Krisp</b>: nickname from Middle High German <i>krisp</i>, <i>krispel</i> ‘curly-haired man’.","Americanized form of German <b>Krisp</b>: from a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Krispin</i> (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crippen","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crespin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Raul, Vidal, Adelina, Alfonso, Amador, Andres, Aniceto, Delfino, Emilio.","Spanish (<b>Crespín</b>): variant of   Crispin  .","French: from the Latin personal name <i>Crispinus</i> (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crispen","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of German <b>Krispin</b>, a cognate of   Crispin  ."]},{"name":"Crispino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Luigi, Carlo, Amato, Angelo, Antonio, Domenico, Fiore, Gennaro, Michelina, Rocco, Sal, Salvator.","Italian (southern): from the personal name <i>Crispino</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, a derivative of the old Roman surname <i>Crispus</i> ‘curly(-headed)’ (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crippin","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crespi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jaime, Juan, Mercedes, Racquel, Alberto, Alejandro, Consuelo, Eduardo, Jose, Jose Manuel, Migdalia, Pedro.  Jewish Aron, Nissim.","Catalan (<b>Crespí</b>): from a personal name, the Catalan equivalent of   Crispin  .","Italian (northern): variant of   Crespo  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Crispyn was born in 1255, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Cryspin, was 35 and his mother, Arundella de Arundel, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Joan Le Waleys. He died on 13 July 1291, at the age of 36."},"et":{"       1255–13 Jul 1291":"1255–13. juuli 1291","1255–1291":"1255–1291","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1283–1325":"1283–1325","1285–1313":"1285–1313","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1325":"1325","1225":"1225","1313":"1313","       1255":"1255","1255":"1255","1320":"1320","13 Jul 1291":"13. juuli 1291","BEF 1291":"enne 1291","England":"England","Devonshire,, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"       1255–13 Jul 1291":"1255–13. heinäkuuta 1291","1255–1291":"1255–1291","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1283–1325":"1283–1325","1285–1313":"1285–1313","1220–1291":"1220–1291","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1325":"1325","1225":"1225","1313":"1313","       1255":"1255","1255":"1255","1320":"1320","13 Jul 1291":"13. heinäkuuta 1291","BEF 1291":"ennen vuotta 1291","England":"England","Devon